[table][tr][th]Title[/th][td]Metroid II - Return of Samus[/td][/tr][tr][th]Composer[/th][td]Ryoji Yoshitomi[/td][/tr][tr][th]System[/th][td]Nintendo Game Boy[/td][/tr][tr][th]Tracks[/th][td]19[/td][/tr][tr][th]Playing time[/th][td]32:58[/td][/tr][tr][th]Pack author[/th][td]sherpa[/td][/tr][tr][th]Pack version[/th][td]1.00[/td][/tr][tr][th]Last Update[/th][td]2015-02-18[/td][/tr][/table]
[align=center][timg]GameBoy/Metroid_II_-_Return_of_Samus_(Game_Boy).png[/timg]
Download [zip]GameBoy/Metroid_II_-_Return_of_Samus_(Game_Boy)[/zip] (76 288 bytes)[/align]
[u:29ezdly1]Pack author's comment[/u:29ezdly1]
A brooding sense of danger. Interesting juxtaposition of silence and sudden tension. This is probably the most challenging pack I have worked on to date. I spent hours looking for pure loops, trying math, reripping tracks, only to conclude, after pouring over midis and text files, that there wasn't one. First time I came across polymeter in a game. Lots of long waits, and each voice seems to have a separate length..I doubt this will ever be performed live, some features are easily produced in electronic music. This showcases the sound capabilities of the gameboy very well..with a wide variety of textures. Some clicks and pops also, which may not have been intentional. Most vgms have simple forms, very few of these tracks do. I aimed for the best spot to trim in the absence of a real loop, aiming for a matchpoint where at least 2-3 voices aligned and the rest were off by as little as possible.

13 Omega Metroid area - cut in a period of silence 3/4 second before the melodic line starts its new cycle. This is during a long period of silence, so it is not very noticeable.

14 Metroid nest  -music has unsymettrical patterns, so the loop is forced
15 Metroids hatched - forced loop/cut just before main voice starts new loop
16 Metroid Queen area - <1000 samples difference in timings (between original and loop)
17 Metroid Queen fight - less than 200 samples difference between timings, nearest points in txt2vgm were over 8000 samples off, not bad considering on either side the sample waits were 2000+ and 17k+
18 Metroid hatchling - hatchet job, displaces drum sample by 6 beats, drums displaced by 16th forward every time the other voices line up…may come very close to proper alignment bt 7-8 min, but i did not attempt to find a pure loop point since this was the last track i worked on and finding exactly where voices align is very time consuming, maybe someone may wish to try.

There are a few others. Now I know why I could never find the loop point when I listened to this as a younger kid. I thought it was just the lack of catchy or obvious melody..but some tracks do take a while to actually loop. I doubt my ear would have noticed anyway.

Enjoy.
Title: Metroid II - Return of Samus

[u:3ncab0mg]Pack author's comment[/u:3ncab0mg]
My thirteenth submission, simply because one of the tracks in this pack stumped me on how to trim it until I found another method I am now familiar with. The oldest Korean Neo Geo game, [i:3ncab0mg]Fight Fever[/i:3ncab0mg], known as [i:3ncab0mg]Wang Jung Wang[/i:3ncab0mg] (왕중왕) in Korea, is sadly not the most well-constructed game on the system. However, it has a decent soundtrack that uses samples borrowed from SNK (who apparently [url=http://www.hardcoregaming101.net/korea/part2/company-viccom.htm:3ncab0mg]trained a team of nine Korean developers for a year[/url:3ncab0mg]), and it's overall good listening. That's more than you can say about [i:3ncab0mg]Legend of Success Joe[/i:3ncab0mg]...

[u:2qv76m7s]Pack author's comment[/u:2qv76m7s]
My fourteenth submission! This is the second game in SNK's longest running series, which introduced Iori Yagami's then-unheard-of style and attitude to the fighting game world, but also featured terrible gameplay balance. However, the soundtrack has improved from the previous game, with better composition and samples and a hint of the kind of soundtracks the series would get in later games with Iori Yagami's now-famous saxophone theme. It should overall be good listening for anyone.

[u:1ccvbl6o]Pack author's comment[/u:1ccvbl6o]
My twenty-seventh submission. This game marks the point when SNK went bankrupt and the series was sold to Korean company Eolith, who then had a new yearly installment produced by former SNK developers on a tighter budget. Sadly, it shows. The soundtrack of mostly 30-second techno loops that resulted remains disliked by the series' fandom to this day. It's not terrible [i:1ccvbl6o]per se[/i:1ccvbl6o], but it's certainly not at the level of the previous games' music or even that of the games following it.

Why is this pack here? Because if this site is to have packs for the entire Neo Geo section of the series, it needs a pack for this game—and [i:1ccvbl6o]someone[/i:1ccvbl6o] had to do it. Have a listen if you want; there are still a few cool tracks on there, such as "0", "I Am the Strongest" or "NESTS, the Rulers of Darkness."
Title: The King of Fighters 2001

[u:3fsbc7d8]Pack author's comment[/u:3fsbc7d8]
My twenty-eighth submission. Still under Eolith's ownership and with the ongoing storyline concluded in [i:3fsbc7d8][topic=2316]2001[/topic][/i:3fsbc7d8], [i:3fsbc7d8]The King of Fighters[/i:3fsbc7d8] received a new "dream match" game that had a little more of a budget—but not much. While there was now enough money for loops more than 30 seconds long, there wasn't enough for good instrumentation and the remixes found in the soundtrack suffer for it especially. However, most of the original stage music is decent, even if they're not as good as the music in the pre-bankruptcy games.

Like [i:3fsbc7d8]2001[/i:3fsbc7d8], this pack is here because having a complete selection of VGM packs for the Neo Geo [i:3fsbc7d8]King of Fighters[/i:3fsbc7d8] games requires a pack for this game. Fortunately, at least the soundtrack's better than last time.

My twenty-ninth submission, for the final Neo Geo game in [i:30mg8trs]The King of Fighters[/i:30mg8trs] series. At this point, SNK returned from bankruptcy as "Playmore", bought the series back, swiftly rebranded themselves as "SNK Playmore", and produced a new game that finally had something resembling a budget. While the instrument samples are still low-quality, the overall composition and instrumentation is markedly improved from the previous two games. With more complexity and a fitting sound for every occasion, this soundtrack can hang with the pre-bankruptcy games in terms of quality and listenability. This pack is strongly recommended.

[u:jmdaaxhw]Pack author's comment[/u:jmdaaxhw]
My thirty-fourth submission is for the black sheep of SNK's entire fighting game catalogue! With its strange and colorful designs, alongside a variant of [i:jmdaaxhw]Fatal Fury[/i:jmdaaxhw]'s multi-plane system, it did not make much of an impact, but like most of SNK's games, it brought in a great soundtrack with a wide variety of genres. A recommended listen! It was followed up with [i:jmdaaxhw][topic=2788]Kizuna Encounter[/topic][/i:jmdaaxhw], which is better known but no less strange than the original!
Title:
Savage Reign /
Fuu'un Mokushiroku: Kakutou Sousei

Happy New Year! To kick off 2015, here's my first VGM rip of the year, Deathbots! An obscure game that I picked up during my graduation ceremony a few years ago...
Quite an obscure soundtrack, but I like it. Even if there's only five songs.
For the Level 3/4/6 song, I let it play 4 times and it doesn't seem to change, so I believe it's the whole song. Let me know if it's not. This was definitely one of my harder rips, as the game's sound engine isn't the greatest. I played everything and it sounded great to me, but if you catch something, please let me know. Thanks!

[u:13x09dd4]Pack author's comment[/u:13x09dd4]
Even though there's only three songs, I think the title screen is the longest title screen song in an NES game; 3:47

The Victory music is also used in Maxi 15 which I just submitted.

When I spoke to Art Cestaro long ago, he said that even though him and George Rucker are credited for music, he (Art) was only a music producer, telling the composer Mike Smith what kind of music he wanted in the game, and George Rucker would program their sound drivers. It makes sense since there's only 3 songs in the entire game.

My seventeenth submission! This pack was created at the request of RichterEX2. [i:1j5jqpr3]Commander Keen in Goodbye, Galaxy! Episode IV: Secret of the Oracle[/i:1j5jqpr3] is the first [i:1j5jqpr3]Commander Keen[/i:1j5jqpr3] to have music, and the soundtrack supplied by Robert Prince is every bit as lighthearted and whimsical as the game itself. This game features the enemy character of the Dopefish, which has since become a recurring industry in-joke with "You've Got to Eat Your Vegetables!!" as its official theme song. This pack also includes two unused tracks from a .zip file supplied by co-programmer John Romero.

[u:2b5ff0k8]Pack author's comment[/u:2b5ff0k8]
The longest and the best (IMHO) out of the EotB trilogy. Amazing what Frank Klepacki did on this soundtrack considering all he had was Visual Composer.

The Ira/Calandra and Catacomb Guard/Catacomb Clerics songs sound the same, but I noticed some differences. For the Ira/Calandra song, I noticed the Calandra song plays louder in some areas. The Catacomb Clerics song is cut off.

There are some sound effects in the game that make me wonder if they count as songs or not (such as the sound when a party member dies.) If someone who's played the game thinks it counts as a song, I'll include it in the rip. I also found another unknown/unused song that plays somewhere in the first part of Temple Darkmoon (MEZANINE.ADL). I thought maybe it played when you went to the resurrection altar, but going there doesn't seem to play anything. If anyone can figure out where the unknown songs play at, you get a free (virtual) cookie!

A huge thanks to Valley Bell for helping me rip this.

[u:r64yid9i]Pack author's comment[/u:r64yid9i]
A couple things to note:

1.) Some songs (Pub Theme 1 & 2, or Witch Death for example) sound glitchy. This is normal in the game. It's because more than one note is trying to play through a single channel.

2.) I was listening to the MT-32 soundtrack on YouTube and noticed there was an 'alternate' version of the Mine - Combat music. However, this is actually just a glitch in the game and is not actually supposed to sound like that. I did rip the alternate version's VGZ (for AdLib/SoundBlaster, of course), but it is not included in this rip.

The game uses the .mus format. Not sure if it's Accolade's or Horror Soft's own. Swapping the title music (mod7.mus) with any other file will play the respected file on the title screen. However, a few of these will not play properly on the title screen and must be accessed in the game (the aforementioned 'alternate' Mine - Combat music). I did play through the entire game to ensure the songs all sound right. If you notice any problems, please let me know and I'd be more than happy to fix them.
Title: WaxWorks

Doing a little comparison with what the Amiga soundtrack sounded like, and the MIDI music files included in the game's folder, it seems strangely enough that the DOS sound driver apparently forced all the music to play at a locked speed, and the Amiga soundtrack was more true to the tempo settings in the MIDIs.
Also, as you will probably notice in the Town track, the playback was a bit buggy and applying a cumulative delay on some instrument tracks. Actually, in this one, the track that got delayed seemed to be 'trying' to readjust itself to the song, but it just kept getting messier. If you play the game you'll know what I mean.

[u:2gptb3ml]Pack author's comment[/u:2gptb3ml]
An early horror themed game. Good music. Very flag driven game, so can't zoom through it to see what the music of some tracks is based on. It's possible some of these are not in game. Unknown composer, but another game from Victor Musical Industries, who worked on such games as The Legendary Axe. Fun Factory (or Project) as it's listed here made the original game, my guess is Victor provided the music. Not sure who ported the code and added the rpg elements.

Wish I knew who the composer was. Some music is recycled, could be the last three tracks are not used in game at all. One track had a somewhat unique loop/song structure, and I don't think the track appears in game.
Title: Shiryou Sensen

Download [zip]Other/Final_Fight_(Sharp_X68000)[/zip] (288 874 bytes)[/align]
[u:13wc5orv]Pack author's comment[/u:13wc5orv]
My twenty-sixth submission is the soundtrack of the Sharp X68000 port of [i:13wc5orv][topic=812]Final Fight[/topic][/i:13wc5orv]—in other words, the port to the computer it was developed on. More specifically, it's the "Internal" version of the soundtrack, which uses the X68000's native YM2151 and Oki MSM6258, as opposed to the optional "MT-32" soundtrack which can be played if you have a Roland MT-32 plugged into your X68000. It's near identical to the arcade version's except for higher-quality samples, making it a more recommended listen than the original!
Title: Final Fight
Composer:
Manami Matsumae, Yoshihiro Sakaguchi,
Harumi Fujita, Junko Tamiya, Yasuaki Fujita,
Hiromitsu Takaoka, Yoko Shimomura

Arsys' X68000 conversion of [i:10amyo8l]Spindizzy Worlds[/i:10amyo8l] has a completely different soundtrack from the Amiga or SNES versions-- and a much lengthier one, with each of the game's 30 stages having a separate background tune!

[u:2eg72ub0]Pack author's comment[/u:2eg72ub0]
My eighth submission to the site. This is the sequel to [i:2eg72ub0][topic=845]Star Gladiator[/topic][/i:2eg72ub0], which attempted to make their 3D fighter play more like a 2D fighter, and did so in the clunkiest fashion possible. It failed catastrophically, due in part to some incredibly obvious corner-cutting and to looking dated compared to the previous year's [i:2eg72ub0]Tekken 3[/i:2eg72ub0], which was only emphasized when it came out on the Dreamcast a year after the [i:2eg72ub0]Soul Calibur[/i:2eg72ub0] remake did. The metal soundtrack may not be as great as the previous game's more varied and cinematic soundtrack, but at least it's a good listen on its own!

Plasma Sword: Nightmare of Bilstein /
Star Gladiator 2: Nightmare of Bilstein

My tenth submission! Capcom's first published 3D fighting game, developed by Arika, which proved successful enough to get one update and two sequels and also introduced the Super Cancel to fighting games. Three composers who mainly worked with Namco up to this point gave it an excellent soundtrack that's mostly jazz fusion. post_text:

Cadillacs: Kyouryuu Shinseiki[/td][/tr][tr][th]Composer[/th][td]Isao Abe, Syun Nishigaki, Kiyoko Yamada[/td][/tr][tr][th]System[/th][td]CP System Dash[/td][/tr][tr][th]Sound Chips[/th][td]QSound[/td][/tr][tr][th]Tracks[/th][td]38[/td][/tr][tr][th]Playing time[/th][td]47:11[/td][/tr][tr][th]Pack author[/th][td]The Green Herring[/td][/tr][tr][th]Pack version[/th][td]1.50[/td][/tr][tr][th]Last Update[/th][td]2016-08-04[/td][/tr][/table]
[align=center][timg]Arcade/Capcom/Cadillacs_and_Dinosaurs_(CP_System_Dash).png[/timg] [timg]Arcade/Capcom/Cadillacs_and_Dinosaurs_(CP_System_Dash)_JP.png[/timg]
Download [zip]Arcade/Capcom/Cadillacs_and_Dinosaurs_(CP_System_Dash)[/zip] (4 916 176 bytes)[/align]
[u:1oc6wx0v]Pack author's comment[/u:1oc6wx0v]
My twenty-second submission! The second CP System Dash game to released and also the second to get a pack here after [topic=790][i:1oc6wx0v]The Punisher[/i:1oc6wx0v][/topic], this game also happens to be a beat-'em-up based on a comic book, specifically on Mark Schultz's [url=http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xenozoic_Tales:1oc6wx0v][i:1oc6wx0v]Xenozoic Tales[/i:1oc6wx0v][/url:1oc6wx0v] (popularly called [i:1oc6wx0v]Cadillacs and Dinosaurs[/i:1oc6wx0v], the name of the first trade paperback). Whereas [i:1oc6wx0v]The Punisher[/i:1oc6wx0v] was based on a gritty crime drama (at least in spirit), [i:1oc6wx0v]Cadillacs and Dinosaurs[/i:1oc6wx0v] is a pulp-influenced tale of high adventure in a world where humans and dinosaurs once again coexist and our heroes fight to protect what's left of the environment from those who seek to harm it for personal gain. This extends to the soundtrack, which is fast-paced to match the gameplay with electric guitar shredding almost everywhere. The QSound chip once again brings this out better than it would have on the CP System, and this pack is overall recommended listening.
Title:
Cadillacs and Dinosaurs /
Cadillacs: Kyouryuu Shinseiki
Composer: Isao Abe, Syun Nishigaki, Kiyoko Yamada

[u:3h4n229g]Pack author's comment[/u:3h4n229g]
Only includes the tracks exclusive to Savior 2.

Had these games already ripped for a long time, but couldn't make up my mind on how to share them until very recently.

Both Vampire Hunter 2 and Savior 2 are technically the same game. However due to the return of Donovan, Pyron, Huitzel/Phobos plus the limited memory of the CPS2, certain members from the original Savior cast got the boot to make room. For Hunter 2, it was most of the new characters introduced in Savior (Lilith still mostly existed for one reason or another), whereas in Savior 2 it was Gallon/J. Talbain, Aulbath/Rikuo, and Sasquatch that were axed. The other big difference between the two are the soundtracks with Savior 2 keeping most of Savior's soundtrack, and Hunter 2 getting Hunter/Nightwarriors' soundtrack.
Title: Vampire Savior 2: The Lord of Vampire

My fortieth submission is a shoot-'em-up by obscure development house East Technology, developers of the notorious [topic=2566][i:1mkh5cnb]Double Dragon 3[/i:1mkh5cnb][/topic]. Besides its unusual player ship design, the game features an excellent FM/ADPCM soundtrack that [i:1mkh5cnb]will[/i:1mkh5cnb] stay with you for a long time. Recommended!

[i:9ikoxr7o]Lethal Enforcers II: Gun Fighters[/i:9ikoxr7o] / [i:9ikoxr7o]Lethal Enforcers II: The Western[/i:9ikoxr7o] is the sequel to a [topic=736]game[/topic] whose pack I submitted as my first pack on this site two years ago on the same day (December 8). This light gun game moves the action from modern-day Chicago to the Wild West, with a completely different soundtrack to accompany it. While we don't know for sure who the composers were and there's no official soundtrack release either, this is a nice Western-themed soundtrack recommended for everyday listening.
